****AIs Response****

That's actually the most important part of this project to understand. Once storage.py clicks, the rest of the application becomes much easier to reason about.

First, what problem is storage.py solving?

Imagine there was no storage.py.

manager = TaskManager()
manager.create_task("Study Python")

The task would exist only while the program is running.

When you close the program:

RAM is cleared
↓

All tasks disappear

That's because Python variables live in memory (RAM).

Persistence means:

"Keep the data even after the program exits."

That's exactly what storage.py is responsible for.

Think of RAM vs Disk

There are two places your data can live.

               Fast
                │
                ▼

        RAM (memory)

        self.tasks

Program closes
↓

Everything disappears

versus

Hard Drive / SSD

tasks.json

Program closes

↓

Still exists tomorrow

The job of storage.py is constantly moving data between these two places.

Disk
 ↓ load()

RAM
 ↓ modify

RAM
 ↓ save()

Disk

So self.tasks is the working copy, while tasks.json is the permanent copy.

