Archive

The application never edits the archive directly. It always edits the working copy first, then synchronizes it back to disk.

Three small requirements to validate your understanding

Instead of giving you the implementation, here are three requirements that exercise different parts of storage.py:

Add a feature that records when a task was last viewed. Whenever a user requests a task's details, persist the timestamp so that it is still available after restarting the application.
Introduce an archive/export capability. Allow the application to save the current set of tasks to a second JSON file without affecting the primary tasks.json file. This will test whether you understand the difference between in-memory data and the destination file.
Persist a new piece of task metadata. Add a new attribute to a task (for example, an estimate, category, or owner) and ensure that it survives a full cycle of creating a task, saving it, closing the application, and loading it again. This will require understanding both serialization (saving) and deserialization (loading).

These three requirements progressively test:

how data flows through the application,
how objects are converted to and from JSON,
and where persistence responsibilities belong. If you can implement all three without breaking the existing architecture, you'll have a solid grasp of how storage.py works.

****My findings****

storage.py persists data by saving all tasks into a local JSON file (tasks.json). On startup, load() reads the file and rebuilds Task objects into self.tasks (in-memory dictionary). self.tasks is the working memory where all operations (add/update/delete) happen first.
Every change modifies self.tasks, not the file directly. After any change, save() is called to persist updates to disk. save() converts all Task objects into JSON-safe dictionaries using TaskEncoder.
Enums and datetime objects are converted into JSON-friendly values (e.g., .value, .isoformat()). The entire task list is rewritten to tasks.json using json.dump(). When loading, TaskDecoder converts JSON dictionaries back into Task objects.
So the system works as: load → work in RAM → rewrite full file on every change.

In the beginning my view was there are files and I should everything, but instead I should be asking questions like what does app.py do, what does storage.py do etc.